# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: soft-actor-critic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In machine learning and optimal control, **reinforcement learning** (**RL**) is concerned with how an intelligent agent should take actions in a dynamic environment in order to maximize a reward signal.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Reinforcement learning is one of the three basic machine learning paradigms, alongside supervised learning and unsupervised learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] While supervised learning and unsupervised learning algorithms respectively attempt to discover patterns in labeled and unlabeled data, reinforcement learning involves training an agent through interactions with its environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] To learn to maximize rewards from these interactions, the agent makes decisions between trying new actions to learn more about the environment (exploration), or using current knowledge of the environment to take the best action (exploitation).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The search for the optimal balance between these two strategies is known as the exploration–exploitation dilemma.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The environment is typically stated in the form of a Markov decision process, as many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The main difference between classical dynamic programming methods and reinforcement learning algorithms is that the latter do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the Markov decision process, and they target large Markov decision processes where exact methods become infeasible.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Due to its generality, reinforcement learning is studied in many disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimization, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, and statistics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The purpose of reinforcement learning is for the agent to learn an optimal (or near-optimal) policy that maximizes the reward function or other user-provided reinforcement signal that accumulates from immediate rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This is similar to processes that appear to occur in animal psychology.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For example, biological brains are hardwired to interpret signals such as pain and hunger as negative reinforcements, and interpret pleasure and food intake as positive reinforcements.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In some circumstances, animals learn to adopt behaviors that optimize these rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This suggests that animals are capable of reinforcement learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A basic reinforcement learning agent interacts with its environment in discrete time steps.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] At each time step t, the agent receives the current state $S_{t}$ and reward $R_{t}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] It then chooses an action $A_{t}$ from the set of available actions, which is subsequently sent to the environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The environment moves to a new state $S_{t+1}$ and the reward $R_{t+1}$ associated with the *transition* $(S_{t},A_{t},S_{t+1})$ is determined.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] that maximizes the expected cumulative reward.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Formulating the problem as a Markov decision process assumes the agent directly observes the current environmental state; in this case, the problem is said to have *full observability*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] If the agent only has access to a subset of states, or if the observed states are corrupted by noise, the agent is said to have *partial observability*, and formally the problem must be formulated as a partially observable Markov decision process.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In both cases, the set of actions available to the agent can be restricted.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For example, the state of an account balance could be restricted to be positive; if the current value of the state is 3 and the state transition attempts to reduce the value by 4, the transition will not be allowed.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] When the agent's performance is compared to that of an agent that acts optimally, the difference in performance yields the notion of regret.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In order to act near optimally, the agent must reason about long-term consequences of its actions (i.e., maximize future rewards), although the immediate reward associated with this might be negative.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Thus, reinforcement learning is particularly well-suited to problems that include a long-term versus short-term reward trade-off.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] It has been applied successfully to various problems, including energy storage, robot control, photovoltaic generators, backgammon, checkers, Go (AlphaGo), and autonomous driving systems.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Two elements make reinforcement learning powerful: the use of samples to optimize performance, and the use of function approximation to deal with large environments.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The first two of these problems could be considered planning problems (since some form of model is available), while the last one could be considered to be a genuine learning problem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] However, reinforcement learning converts both planning problems to machine learning problems.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The trade-off between exploration and exploitation has been most thoroughly studied through the multi-armed bandit problem and for finite state space Markov decision processes in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Reinforcement learning requires clever exploration mechanisms; randomly selecting actions, without reference to an estimated probability distribution, shows poor performance.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The case of (small) finite Markov decision processes is relatively well understood.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] However, due to the lack of algorithms that scale well with the number of states (or scale to problems with infinite state spaces), simple exploration methods are the most practical.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] One such method is $\varepsilon$ -greedy, where $0<\varepsilon <1$ is a parameter controlling the amount of exploration vs. exploitation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] With probability $1-\varepsilon$ , exploitation is chosen, and the agent chooses the action that it believes has the best long-term effect (ties between actions are broken uniformly at random).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Alternatively, with probability $\varepsilon$ , exploration is chosen, and the action is chosen uniformly at random. $\varepsilon$ is usually a fixed parameter but can be adjusted either according to a schedule (making the agent explore progressively less), or adaptively based on heuristics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Even if the issue of exploration is disregarded and even if the state was observable (assumed hereafter), the problem remains to use past experience to find out which actions lead to higher cumulative rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The policy map gives the probability of taking action a when in state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] There are also deterministic policies $\pi$ for which $\pi (s)$ denotes the action that should be played at state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The state-value function $V_{\pi }(s)$ is defined as, *expected discounted return* starting with state s , i.e. $S_{0}=s$ , and successively following policy $\pi$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Hence, roughly speaking, the value function estimates "how good" it is to be in a given state.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] where $R_{t+1}$ is the reward for transitioning from state $S_{t}$ to $S_{t+1}$ , $0\leq \gamma <1$ is the discount rate. $\gamma$ is less than 1, so rewards in the distant future are weighted less than rewards in the immediate future.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The algorithm must find a policy with maximum expected discounted return.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] From the theory of Markov decision processes it is known that, without loss of generality, the search can be restricted to the set of so-called *stationary* policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A policy is *stationary* if the action-distribution returned by it depends only on the last state visited (from the observation agent's history).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The search can be further restricted to *deterministic* stationary policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A *deterministic stationary* policy deterministically selects actions based on the current state.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Since any such policy can be identified with a mapping from the set of states to the set of actions, these policies can be identified with such mappings with no loss of generality.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] One problem with this is that the number of policies can be large, or even infinite.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Another is that the variance of the returns may be large, which requires many samples to accurately estimate the discounted return of each policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These problems can be ameliorated if we assume some structure and allow samples generated from one policy to influence the estimates made for others.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The two main approaches for achieving this are value function estimation and direct policy search.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Value function approaches attempt to find a policy that maximizes the discounted return by maintaining a set of estimates of expected discounted returns $\operatorname {\mathbb {E} } [G]$ for some policy (usually either the "current" [on-policy] or the optimal [off-policy] one).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These methods rely on the theory of Markov decision processes, where optimality is defined in a sense stronger than the one above: A policy is optimal if it achieves the best-expected discounted return from *any* initial state (i.e., initial distributions play no role in this definition).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Again, an optimal policy can always be found among stationary policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] where G stands for the discounted return associated with following $\pi$ from the initial state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A policy that achieves these optimal state-values in each state is called *optimal*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Clearly, a policy that is optimal in this sense is also optimal in the sense that it maximizes the expected discounted return, since $V^{*}(s)=\max _{\pi }\mathbb {E} [G\mid s,\pi ]$ , where s is a state randomly sampled from the distribution $\mu$ of initial states (so $\mu (s)=\Pr(S_{0}=s)$ ).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Although state-values suffice to define optimality, it is useful to define action-values.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] where G now stands for the random discounted return associated with first taking action a in state s and following $\pi$ , thereafter.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The theory of Markov decision processes states that if $\pi ^{*}$ is an optimal policy, we act optimally (take the optimal action) by choosing the action from $Q^{\pi ^{*}}(s,\cdot )$ with the highest action-value at each state, s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The *action-value function* of such an optimal policy ( $Q^{\pi ^{*}}$ ) is called the *optimal action-value function* and is commonly denoted by $Q^{*}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In summary, the knowledge of the optimal action-value function alone suffices to know how to act optimally.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Assuming full knowledge of the Markov decision process, the two basic approaches to compute the optimal action-value function are value iteration and policy iteration.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Both algorithms compute a sequence of functions $Q_{k}$ ( $k=0,1,2,\ldots$ ) that converge to $Q^{*}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Computing these functions involves computing expectations over the whole state-space, which is impractical for all but the smallest (finite) Markov decision processes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In reinforcement learning methods, expectations are approximated by averaging over samples and using function approximation techniques to cope with the need to represent value functions over large state-action spaces.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Monte Carlo methods are used to solve reinforcement learning problems by averaging sample returns.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Unlike methods that require full knowledge of the environment's dynamics, Monte Carlo methods rely solely on actual or simulated experience—sequences of states, actions, and rewards obtained from interaction with an environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This makes them applicable in situations where the complete dynamics are unknown.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Learning from actual experience does not require prior knowledge of the environment and can still lead to optimal behavior.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] When using simulated experience, only a model capable of generating sample transitions is required, rather than a full specification of transition probabilities, which is necessary for dynamic programming methods.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Monte Carlo methods apply to episodic tasks, where experience is divided into episodes that eventually terminate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Policy and value function updates occur only after the completion of an episode, making these methods incremental on an episode-by-episode basis, though not on a step-by-step (online) basis.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The term "Monte Carlo" generally refers to any method involving random sampling; however, in this context, it specifically refers to methods that compute averages from *complete* returns, rather than *partial* returns.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These methods function similarly to the bandit algorithms, in which returns are averaged for each state-action pair.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The key difference is that actions taken in one state affect the returns of subsequent states within the same episode, making the problem non-stationary.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] To address this non-stationarity, Monte Carlo methods use the framework of general policy iteration (GPI).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] While dynamic programming computes value functions using full knowledge of the Markov decision process, Monte Carlo methods learn these functions through sample returns.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The value functions and policies interact similarly to dynamic programming to achieve optimality, first addressing the prediction problem and then extending to policy improvement and control, all based on sampled experience.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The first problem is corrected by allowing the procedure to change the policy (at some or all states) before the values settle.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This too may be problematic as it might prevent convergence.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Most current algorithms do this, giving rise to the class of *generalized policy iteration* algorithms.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Many *actor-critic* methods belong to this category.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The second issue can be corrected by allowing trajectories to contribute to any state-action pair in them.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This may also help to some extent with the third problem, although a better solution when returns have high variance is Sutton's temporal difference (TD) methods that are based on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The computation in TD methods can be incremental (when after each transition the memory is changed and the transition is thrown away), or batch (when the transitions are batched and the estimates are computed once based on the batch).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Batch methods, such as the least-squares temporal difference method, may use the information in the samples better, while incremental methods are the only choice when batch methods are infeasible due to their high computational or memory complexity.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Some methods try to combine the two approaches.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Methods based on temporal differences also overcome the fourth issue.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Another problem specific to TD comes from their reliance on the recursive Bellman equation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Most TD methods have a so-called $\lambda$ parameter $(0\leq \lambda \leq 1)$ that can continuously interpolate between Monte Carlo methods that do not rely on the Bellman equations and the basic TD methods that rely entirely on the Bellman equations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This can be effective in palliating this issue.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In order to address the fifth issue, *function approximation methods* are used.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] *Linear function approximation* starts with a mapping $\phi$ that assigns a finite-dimensional vector to each state-action pair.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The algorithms then adjust the weights, instead of adjusting the values associated with the individual state-action pairs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Methods based on ideas from nonparametric statistics (which can be seen to construct their own features) have been explored.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Value iteration can also be used as a starting point, giving rise to the Q-learning algorithm and its many variants.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Including Deep Q-learning methods when a neural network is used to represent Q, with various applications in stochastic search problems.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The problem with using action-values is that they may need highly precise estimates of the competing action values that can be hard to obtain when the returns are noisy, though this problem is mitigated to some extent by temporal difference methods.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Using the so-called compatible function approximation method compromises generality and efficiency.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] An alternative method is to search directly in (some subset of) the policy space, in which case the problem becomes a case of stochastic optimization.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The two approaches available are gradient-based and gradient-free methods.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Gradient-based methods (*policy gradient methods*) start with a mapping from a finite-dimensional (parameter) space to the space of policies: given the parameter vector $\theta$ , let $\pi _{\theta }$ denote the policy associated to $\theta$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Defining the performance function by $\rho (\theta )=\rho ^{\pi _{\theta }}$ under mild conditions this function will be differentiable as a function of the parameter vector $\theta$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] If the gradient of $\rho$ was known, one could use gradient ascent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Since an analytic expression for the gradient is not available, only a noisy estimate is available.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Such an estimate can be constructed in many ways, giving rise to algorithms such as Williams's REINFORCE method (which is known as the likelihood ratio method in the simulation-based optimization literature).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A large class of methods avoids relying on gradient information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These include simulated annealing, cross-entropy search or methods of evolutionary computation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Many gradient-free methods can achieve (in theory and in the limit) a global optimum.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Policy search methods may converge slowly given noisy data.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For example, this happens in episodic problems when the trajectories are long and the variance of the returns is large.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Value-function based methods that rely on temporal differences might help in this case.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In recent years, *actor–critic methods* have been proposed and performed well on various problems.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Policy search methods have been used in the robotics context.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Many policy search methods may get stuck in local optima (as they are based on local search).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Finally, all of the above methods can be combined with algorithms that first learn a model of the Markov decision process, the probability of each next state given an action taken from an existing state.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For instance, the Dyna algorithm learns a model from experience, and uses that to provide more modelled transitions for a value function, in addition to the real transitions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Such methods can sometimes be extended to use of non-parametric models, such as when the transitions are simply stored and "replayed" to the learning algorithm.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Model-based methods can be more computationally intensive than model-free approaches, and their utility can be limited by the extent to which the Markov decision process can be learnt.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] There are other ways to use models than to update a value function.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For instance, in model predictive control the model is used to update the behavior directly.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The costly exploration needed to learn an optimal policy can be reduced if some supervised data is available.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This can be achieved for instance by learning a crude control policy and using this to initialize the Q table intelligently instead of with zeros.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Both the asymptotic and finite-sample behaviors of most algorithms are well understood.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Algorithms with provably (i.e. in a way that can be proved) good online performance (addressing the exploration issue) are known.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Efficient exploration of Markov decision processes is given in Burnetas and Katehakis (1997).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Finite-time performance bounds have also appeared for many algorithms, but these bounds are expected to be rather loose and thus more work is needed to better understand the relative advantages and limitations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For incremental algorithms, asymptotic convergence issues have been settled.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Temporal-difference-based algorithms converge under a wider set of conditions than was previously possible (for example, when used with arbitrary, smooth function approximation).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Associative reinforcement learning tasks combine facets of stochastic learning automata tasks and supervised learning pattern classification tasks.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In associative reinforcement learning tasks, the learning system interacts in a closed loop with its environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This approach extends reinforcement learning by using a deep neural network and without explicitly designing the state space.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The work on learning ATARI games by Google DeepMind increased attention to deep reinforcement learning or end-to-end reinforcement learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Adversarial deep reinforcement learning is an active area of research in reinforcement learning focusing on vulnerabilities of learned policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In this research area some studies initially showed that reinforcement learning policies are susceptible to imperceptible adversarial manipulations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] While some methods have been proposed to overcome these susceptibilities, in the most recent studies it has been shown that these proposed solutions are far from providing an accurate representation of current vulnerabilities of deep reinforcement learning policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] By introducing fuzzy inference in reinforcement learning, approximating the state-action value function with fuzzy rules in continuous space becomes possible.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The IF - THEN form of fuzzy rules make this approach suitable for expressing the results in a form close to natural language.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Extending FRL with Fuzzy Rule Interpolation allows the use of reduced size sparse fuzzy rule-bases to emphasize cardinal rules (most important state-action values).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In inverse reinforcement learning (IRL), no reward function is given.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Instead, the reward function is inferred given an observed behavior from an expert.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The idea is to mimic observed behavior, which is often optimal or close to optimal.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] One popular IRL paradigm is named maximum entropy inverse reinforcement learning (MaxEnt IRL).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] MaxEnt IRL estimates the parameters of a linear model of the reward function by maximizing the entropy of the probability distribution of observed trajectories subject to constraints related to matching expected feature counts.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Recently it has been shown that MaxEnt IRL is a particular case of a more general framework named random utility inverse reinforcement learning (RU-IRL).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] RU-IRL is based on random utility theory and Markov decision processes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The utility function is modeled as a random variable to account for the ignorance of the observer regarding the features the observed agent actually considers in its utility function.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) is a form of reinforcement learning concerned with conflicting alternatives.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] It is distinct from multi-objective optimization in that it is concerned with agents acting in environments.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Safe reinforcement learning (SRL) can be defined as the process of learning policies that maximize the expectation of the return in problems in which it is important to ensure reasonable system performance and/or respect safety constraints during the learning and/or deployment processes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] An alternative approach is risk-averse reinforcement learning, where instead of the *expected* return, a *risk-measure* of the return is optimized, such as the conditional value at risk (CVaR).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In addition to mitigating risk, the CVaR objective increases robustness to model uncertainties.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] However, CVaR optimization in risk-averse RL requires special care, to prevent gradient bias and blindness to success.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Self-reinforcement learning (or self-learning), is a learning paradigm which does not use the concept of immediate reward $R_{a}(s,s')$ after transition from s to $s'$ with action a .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] It does not use an external reinforcement, it only uses the agent internal self-reinforcement.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The internal self-reinforcement is provided by mechanism of feelings and emotions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In the learning process emotions are backpropagated by a mechanism of secondary reinforcement.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The learning equation does not include the immediate reward, it only includes the state evaluation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Compute state evaluation $v(s')$ of how good it is to be in the consequence situation $s'$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Initial conditions of the memory are received as input from the genetic environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] It is a system with only one input (situation), and only one output (action, or behavior).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Self-reinforcement (self-learning) was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-reinforcement learning, named Crossbar Adaptive Array (CAA).
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence states.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Efficient comparison of RL algorithms is essential for research, deployment and monitoring of RL systems.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] To compare different algorithms on a given environment, an agent can be trained for each algorithm.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Since the performance is sensitive to implementation details, all algorithms should be implemented as closely as possible to each other.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] After the training is finished, the agents can be run on a sample of test episodes, and their scores (returns) can be compared.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Since episodes are typically assumed to be i.i.d, standard statistical tools can be used for hypothesis testing, such as T-test and permutation test.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This requires to accumulate all the rewards within an episode into a single number—the episodic return.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] However, this causes a loss of information, as different time-steps are averaged together, possibly with different levels of noise.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Whenever the noise level varies across the episode, the statistical power can be improved significantly, by weighting the rewards according to their estimated noise.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Despite significant advancements, reinforcement learning (RL) continues to face several challenges and limitations that hinder its widespread application in real-world scenarios.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] RL algorithms often require a large number of interactions with the environment to learn effective policies, leading to high computational costs and time-intensive to train the agent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] For instance, OpenAI's Dota-playing bot utilized thousands of years of simulated gameplay to achieve human-level performance.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Techniques like experience replay and curriculum learning have been proposed to reduce sample inefficiency, but these techniques add more complexity and are not always sufficient for real-world applications.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Training RL models, particularly for deep neural network-based models, can be unstable and prone to divergence.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A small change in the policy or environment can lead to extreme fluctuations in performance, making it difficult to achieve consistent results.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This instability is further enhanced in the case of the continuous or high-dimensional action space, where the learning step becomes more complex and less predictable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The RL agents trained in specific environments often struggle to generalize their learned policies to new, unseen scenarios.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This is the major setback preventing the application of RL to dynamic real-world environments where adaptability is crucial.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] The challenge is to develop such algorithms that can transfer knowledge across tasks and environments without extensive retraining.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Designing appropriate reward functions is critical in RL because poorly designed reward functions can lead to unintended behaviors.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In addition, RL systems trained on biased data may perpetuate existing biases and lead to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Both of these issues requires careful consideration of reward structures and data sources to ensure fairness and desired behaviors.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] In recent years Since the early 2020s, reinforcement learning has become a significant concept in natural language processing (NLP), where tasks are often sequential decision-making rather than static classification.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Reinforcement learning is where an agent take actions in an environment to maximize the accumulation of rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This framework is best fit for many NLP tasks, including dialogue generation, text summarization, and machine translation, where the quality of the output depends on optimizing long-term or human-centered goals rather than the prediction of single correct label.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Early application of RL in NLP emerged in dialogue systems, where conversation was determined as a series of actions optimized for fluency and coherence.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These early attempts, including policy gradient and sequence-level training techniques, laid a foundation for the broader application of reinforcement learning to other areas of NLP.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] A major breakthrough happened with the introduction of reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), a method in which human feedback ratings are used to train a reward model that guides the RL agent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] Unlike traditional rule-based or supervised systems, RLHF allows models to align their behavior with human judgments on complex and subjective tasks.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This technique was initially used in the development of InstructGPT, an effective language model trained to follow human instructions and later in ChatGPT which incorporates RLHF for improving output responses and ensuring safety.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] More recently, researchers have explored the use of offline RL in NLP to improve dialogue systems without the need of live human interaction.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] These methods optimize for user engagement, coherence, and diversity based on past conversation logs and pre-trained reward models.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] One example is DeepSeek-R1, which incorporates multi-stage training and cold-start data before RL.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] DeepSeek-R1 achieves performance comparable to OpenAI-o1-1217 on reasoning tasks.
[src:soft-actor-critic/actor-critic-method] This model was trained via large-scale RL without supervised fine-tuning (SFT) as a preliminary step.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In information theory, the **entropy** of a random variable quantifies the average level of uncertainty or information associated with the variable's potential states or possible outcomes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This measures the expected amount of information needed to describe the state of the variable, considering the distribution of probabilities across all potential states.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The choice of base for $\log$ , the logarithm, varies for different applications.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Base 2 gives the unit of bits (or "shannons"), while base *e* gives "natural units" nat, and base 10 gives units of "dits", "bans", or "hartleys".
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] An equivalent definition of entropy is the expected value of the self-information of a variable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The concept of information entropy was introduced by Claude Shannon in his 1948 paper "A Mathematical Theory of Communication", and is also referred to as **Shannon entropy**.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's theory defines a data communication system composed of three elements: a source of data, a communication channel, and a receiver.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The "fundamental problem of communication" – as expressed by Shannon – is for the receiver to be able to identify what data was generated by the source, based on the signal it receives through the channel.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon considered various ways to encode, compress, and transmit messages from a data source, and proved in his source coding theorem that the entropy represents an absolute mathematical limit on how well data from the source can be losslessly compressed onto a perfectly noiseless channel.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon strengthened this result considerably for noisy channels in his noisy-channel coding theorem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy in information theory is directly analogous to the entropy in statistical thermodynamics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The analogy results when the values of the random variable designate energies of microstates, so Gibbs's formula for the entropy is formally identical to Shannon's formula.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy has relevance to other areas of mathematics such as combinatorics and machine learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The definition can be derived from a set of axioms establishing that entropy should be a measure of how informative the average outcome of a variable is.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For a continuous random variable, differential entropy is analogous to entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The definition $\mathbb {E} [-\log p(X)]$ generalizes the above.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The core idea of information theory is that the "informational value" of a communicated message depends on the degree to which the content of the message is surprising.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If a highly likely event occurs, the message carries very little information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] On the other hand, if a highly unlikely event occurs, the message is much more informative.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For instance, the knowledge that some particular number *will not* be the winning number of a lottery provides very little information, because any particular chosen number will almost certainly not win.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] However, knowledge that a particular number *will* win a lottery has high informational value because it communicates the occurrence of a very low probability event.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The *information content,* also called the *surprisal* or *self-information,* of an event E is a function that increases as the probability $p(E)$ of an event decreases.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] When $p(E)$ is close to 1, the surprisal of the event is low, but if $p(E)$ is close to 0, the surprisal of the event is high.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This relationship is described by the function $\log \left({\frac {1}{p(E)}}\right),$ where $\log$ is the logarithm, which gives 0 surprise when the probability of the event is 1.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In fact, log is the only function that satisfies a specific set of conditions defined in section *§ Characterization*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy measures the expected (i.e., average) amount of information conveyed by identifying the outcome of a random trial.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This implies that rolling a die has higher entropy than tossing a coin because each outcome of a single die roll has smaller probability ( $p=1/6$ ) than each outcome of a coin toss ( $p=1/2$ ).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Consider a coin with probability *p* of landing on heads and probability 1 − *p* of landing on tails.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The maximum surprise is when *p* = 1/2, for which one outcome is not expected over the other.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In this case a coin flip has an entropy of one bit (similarly, one trit with equiprobable values contains $\log _{2}3$ (about 1.58496) bits of information because it can have one of three values).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The minimum surprise is when *p* = 0 (impossibility) or *p* = 1 (certainty) and the entropy is zero bits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] When the entropy is zero, there is no uncertainty at all – no freedom of choice – no information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Other values of *p* give entropies between zero and one bits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Information theory is useful to calculate the smallest amount of information required to convey a message, as in data compression.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, consider the transmission of sequences comprising the 4 characters 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D' over a binary channel.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If all 4 letters are equally likely (25%), one cannot do better than using two bits to encode each letter.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] However, if the probabilities of each letter are unequal, say 'A' occurs with 70% probability, 'B' with 26%, and 'C' and 'D' with 2% each, one could assign variable length codes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] With this representation, 70% of the time only one bit needs to be sent, 26% of the time two bits, and only 4% of the time 3 bits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] On average, fewer than 2 bits are required since the entropy is lower (owing to the high prevalence of 'A' followed by 'B' – together 96% of characters).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The calculation of the sum of probability-weighted log probabilities measures and captures this effect.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] English text, treated as a string of characters, has fairly low entropy; i.e. it is fairly predictable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] We can be fairly certain that, for example, 'e' will be far more common than 'z', that the combination 'qu' will be much more common than any other combination with a 'q' in it, and that the combination 'th' will be more common than 'z', 'q', or 'qu'.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] After the first few letters one can often guess the rest of the word.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] English text has between 0.6 and 1.3 bits of entropy per character of the message.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Here $\mathbb {E}$ is the expected value operator, and I is the information content of *X*. $\operatorname {I} (X)$ is itself a random variable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy can explicitly be written as: $\mathrm {H} (X)=-\sum _{x\in {\mathcal {X}}}p(x)\log _{b}p(x),$ where *b* is the base of the logarithm used.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Common values of *b* are 2, Euler's number *e*, and 10, and the corresponding units of entropy are the bits for *b* = 2, nats for *b* = *e*, and bans for *b* = 10.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This quantity should be understood as the remaining randomness in the random variable X given the random variable Y .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy can be formally defined in the language of measure theory as follows: Let $(X,\Sigma ,\mu )$ be a probability space.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A $\mu$ -almost partition is a set family $P\subseteq {\mathcal {P}}(X)$ such that $\mu (\bigcup P)=1$ and $\mu (A\cap B)=0$ for all distinct $A,B\in P$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy of M is $\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(M)=\sup _{P\subseteq M}\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(P).$ Finally, the entropy of the probability space is $\mathrm {H} _{\mu }(\Sigma )$ , that is, the entropy with respect to $\mu$ of the sigma-algebra of *all* measurable subsets of X .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Consider tossing a coin with known, not necessarily fair, probabilities of coming up heads or tails; this can be modeled as a Bernoulli process.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy of the unknown result of the next toss of the coin is maximized if the coin is fair (that is, if heads and tails both have equal probability 1/2).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This is the situation of maximum uncertainty as it is most difficult to predict the outcome of the next toss; the result of each toss of the coin delivers one full bit of information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] However, if we know the coin is not fair, but comes up heads or tails with probabilities *p* and *q*, where *p* ≠ *q*, then there is less uncertainty.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Every time it is tossed, one side is more likely to come up than the other.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The reduced uncertainty is quantified in a lower entropy: on average each toss of the coin delivers less than one full bit of information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Uniform probability yields maximum uncertainty and therefore maximum entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy, then, can only decrease from the value associated with uniform probability.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The extreme case is that of a double-headed coin that never comes up tails, or a double-tailed coin that never results in a head.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy is zero: each toss of the coin delivers no new information as the outcome of each coin toss is always certain.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] To understand the meaning of −Σ *p**i* log(*p**i*), first define an information function I in terms of an event *i* with probability *p**i*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] I(1) = 0: events that always occur do not communicate information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] I(*p*1·*p*2) = I(*p*1) + I(*p*2): the information learned from independent events is the sum of the information learned from each event.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] I(*p*) is a twice continuously differentiable function of p.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Given two independent events, if the first event can yield one of *n* equiprobable outcomes and another has one of *m* equiprobable outcomes then there are *mn* equiprobable outcomes of the joint event.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This means that if log2(*n*) bits are needed to encode the first value and log2(*m*) to encode the second, one needs log2(*mn*) = log2(*m*) + log2(*n*) to encode both.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In fact, the only possible values of $\operatorname {I}$ are $\operatorname {I} (u)=k\log u$ for $k<0$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Additionally, choosing a value for *k* is equivalent to choosing a value $x>1$ for $k=-1/\log x$ , so that *x* corresponds to the base for the logarithm.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Thus, entropy is characterized by the above four properties.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The different units of information (bits for the binary logarithm log2, nats for the natural logarithm ln, bans for the decimal logarithm log10 and so on) are constant multiples of each other.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For instance, in case of a fair coin toss, heads provides log2(2) = 1 bit of information, which is approximately 0.693 nats or 0.301 decimal digits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Because of additivity, *n* tosses provide *n* bits of information, which is approximately 0.693*n* nats or 0.301*n* decimal digits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The *meaning* of the events observed (the meaning of *messages*) does not matter in the definition of entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy only takes into account the probability of observing a specific event, so the information it encapsulates is information about the underlying probability distribution, not the meaning of the events themselves.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Another characterization of entropy uses the following properties.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Symmetry: H should be unchanged if the outcomes *x**i* are re-ordered.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Choosing *k* = *n*, *b*1 = ... = *b**n* = 1 this implies that the entropy of a certain outcome is zero: Η1(1) = 0.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This implies that the efficiency of a source set with *n* symbols can be defined simply as being equal to its *n*-ary entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] See also Redundancy (information theory).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The characterization here imposes an additive property with respect to a partition of a set.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Meanwhile, the conditional probability is defined in terms of a multiplicative property, $P(A\mid B)\cdot P(B)=P(A\cap B)$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Observe that a logarithm mediates between these two operations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The conditional entropy and related quantities inherit simple relation, in turn.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The measure theoretic definition in the previous section defined the entropy as a sum over expected surprisals $\mu (A)\cdot \ln \mu (A)$ for an extremal partition.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Here the logarithm is ad hoc and the entropy is not a measure in itself.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] At least in the information theory of a binary string, $\log _{2}$ lends itself to practical interpretations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Motivated by such relations, a plethora of related and competing quantities have been defined.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, David Ellerman's analysis of a "logic of partitions" defines a competing measure in structures dual to that of subsets of a universal set.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Information is quantified as "dits" (distinctions), a measure on partitions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] "Dits" can be converted into Shannon's bits, to get the formulas for conditional entropy, and so on.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Additivity: $\mathrm {H} (X,Y)=\mathrm {H} (X)+\mathrm {H} (Y)$ when the random variables $X,Y$ are independent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It was shown that any function $\mathrm {H}$ satisfying the above properties must be a constant multiple of Shannon entropy, with a non-negative constant.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Compared to the previously mentioned characterizations of entropy, this characterization focuses on the properties of entropy as a function of random variables (subadditivity and additivity), rather than the properties of entropy as a function of the probability vector $p_{1},\ldots ,p_{n}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It is worth noting that if we drop the "small for small probabilities" property, then $\mathrm {H}$ must be a non-negative linear combination of the Shannon entropy and the Hartley entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The inspiration for adopting the word *entropy* in information theory came from the close resemblance between Shannon's formula and very similar known formulae from statistical mechanics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In statistical thermodynamics the most general formula for the thermodynamic entropy *S* of a thermodynamic system is the Gibbs entropy $S=-k_{\text{B}}\sum _{i}p_{i}\ln p_{i}\,,$ where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, and *p**i* is the probability of a microstate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Willard Gibbs in 1878 after earlier work by Ludwig Boltzmann (1872).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The Gibbs entropy translates over almost unchanged into the world of quantum physics to give the von Neumann entropy introduced by John von Neumann in 1927: $S=-k_{\text{B}}\,{\rm {Tr}}(\rho \ln \rho )\,,$ where ρ is the density matrix of the quantum mechanical system and Tr is the trace.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] At an everyday practical level, the links between information entropy and thermodynamic entropy are not evident.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Physicists and chemists are apt to be more interested in *changes* in entropy as a system spontaneously evolves away from its initial conditions, in accordance with the second law of thermodynamics, rather than an unchanging probability distribution.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] As the minuteness of the Boltzmann constant *k*B indicates, the changes in *S* / *k*B for even tiny amounts of substances in chemical and physical processes represent amounts of entropy that are extremely large compared to anything in data compression or signal processing.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In classical thermodynamics, entropy is defined in terms of macroscopic measurements and makes no reference to any probability distribution, which is central to the definition of information entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It is assumed that each microstate is equally likely, so that the probability of a given microstate is *p**i* = 1/*W*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] When these probabilities are substituted into the above expression for the Gibbs entropy (or equivalently *k*B times the Shannon entropy), Boltzmann's equation results.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In information theoretic terms, the information entropy of a system is the amount of "missing" information needed to determine a microstate, given the macrostate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Adding heat to a system increases its thermodynamic entropy because it increases the number of possible microscopic states of the system that are consistent with the measurable values of its macroscopic variables, making any complete state description longer.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] (See article: *maximum entropy thermodynamics*).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Landauer's principle imposes a lower bound on the amount of heat a computer must generate to process a given amount of information, though modern computers are far less efficient.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's definition of entropy, when applied to an information source, can determine the minimum channel capacity required to reliably transmit the source as encoded binary digits.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's entropy measures the information contained in a message as opposed to the portion of the message that is determined (or predictable).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Examples of the latter include redundancy in language structure or statistical properties relating to the occurrence frequencies of letter or word pairs, triplets etc.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The minimum channel capacity can be realized in theory by using the typical set or in practice using Huffman, Lempel–Ziv or arithmetic coding.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] (See also Kolmogorov complexity.) In practice, compression algorithms deliberately include some judicious redundancy in the form of checksums to protect against errors.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy rate of a data source is the average number of bits per symbol needed to encode it.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's experiments with human predictors show an information rate between 0.6 and 1.3 bits per character in English; the PPM compression algorithm can achieve a compression ratio of 1.5 bits per character in English text.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If a compression scheme is lossless – one in which you can always recover the entire original message by decompression – then a compressed message has the same quantity of information as the original but is communicated in fewer characters.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It has more information (higher entropy) per character.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A compressed message has less redundancy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's source coding theorem states a lossless compression scheme cannot compress messages, on average, to have *more* than one bit of information per bit of message, but that any value *less* than one bit of information per bit of message can be attained by employing a suitable coding scheme.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The entropy of a message per bit multiplied by the length of that message is a measure of how much total information the message contains.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon's theorem also implies that no lossless compression scheme can shorten *all* messages.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If some messages come out shorter, at least one must come out longer due to the pigeonhole principle.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A 2011 study in *Science* estimates the world's technological capacity to store and communicate optimally compressed information normalized on the most effective compression algorithms available in the year 2007, therefore estimating the entropy of the technologically available sources.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The authors estimate humankind technological capacity to store information (fully entropically compressed) in 1986 and again in 2007.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] They break the information into three categories—to store information on a medium, to receive information through one-way broadcast networks, or to exchange information through two-way telecommunications networks.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy is one of several ways to measure biodiversity and is applied in the form of the Shannon index.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A diversity index is a quantitative statistical measure of how many different types exist in a dataset, such as species in a community, accounting for ecological richness, evenness, and dominance.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Specifically, Shannon entropy is the logarithm of 1D, the true diversity index with parameter equal to 1.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The Shannon index is related to the proportional abundances of types.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It is important not to confuse the above concepts.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Often it is only clear from context which one is meant.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, when someone says that the "entropy" of the English language is about 1 bit per character, they are actually modeling the English language as a stochastic process and talking about its entropy *rate*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Shannon himself used the term in this way.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If very large blocks are used, the estimate of per-character entropy rate may become artificially low because the probability distribution of the sequence is not known exactly; it is only an estimate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] As a practical code, this corresponds to assigning each book a unique identifier and using it in place of the text of the book whenever one wants to refer to the book.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The key idea is that the complexity of the probabilistic model must be considered.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Kolmogorov complexity is a theoretical generalization of this idea that allows the consideration of the information content of a sequence independent of any particular probability model; it considers the shortest program for a universal computer that outputs the sequence.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A code that achieves the entropy rate of a sequence for a given model, plus the codebook (i.e. the probabilistic model), is one such program, but it may not be the shortest.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The Fibonacci sequence is 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, .... treating the sequence as a message and each number as a symbol, there are almost as many symbols as there are characters in the message, giving an entropy of approximately log2(*n*).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In cryptanalysis, entropy is often roughly used as a measure of the unpredictability of a cryptographic key, though its real uncertainty is unmeasurable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, a 128-bit key that is uniformly and randomly generated has 128 bits of entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It also takes (on average) $2^{127}$ guesses to break by brute force.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy fails to capture the number of guesses required if the possible keys are not chosen uniformly.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Instead, a measure called *guesswork* can be used to measure the effort required for a brute force attack.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Other problems may arise from non-uniform distributions used in cryptography.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, a 1,000,000-digit binary one-time pad using exclusive or.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If the pad has 1,000,000 bits of entropy, it is perfect.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If the pad has 999,999 bits of entropy, evenly distributed (each individual bit of the pad having 0.999999 bits of entropy) it may provide good security.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] But if the pad has 999,999 bits of entropy, where the first bit is fixed and the remaining 999,999 bits are perfectly random, the first bit of the ciphertext will not be encrypted at all.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A common way to define entropy for text is based on the Markov model of text.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] where *i* is a **state** (certain preceding characters) and $p_{i}(j)$ is the probability of *j* given *i* as the previous character.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A source set ${\mathcal {X}}$ with a non-uniform distribution will have less entropy than the same set with a uniform distribution (i.e. the "optimized alphabet").
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Efficiency has utility in quantifying the effective use of a communication channel.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This formulation is also referred to as the normalized entropy, as the entropy is divided by the maximum entropy ${\log _{b}(n)}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Furthermore, the efficiency is indifferent to the choice of (positive) base *b*, as indicated by the insensitivity within the final logarithm above thereto.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The Shannon entropy is restricted to random variables taking discrete values.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This is the differential entropy (or continuous entropy).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A precursor of the continuous entropy *h*[*f*] is the expression for the functional *Η* in the H-theorem of Boltzmann.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Although the analogy between both functions is suggestive, the following question must be set: is the differential entropy a valid extension of the Shannon discrete entropy?
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Differential entropy lacks a number of properties that the Shannon discrete entropy has – it can even be negative – and corrections have been suggested, notably limiting density of discrete points.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In order to obtain a generally finite measure as the bin size goes to zero.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In the discrete case, the bin size is the (implicit) width of each of the *n* (finite or infinite) bins whose probabilities are denoted by *p**n*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] As the continuous domain is generalized, the width must be made explicit.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] To do this, start with a continuous function *f* discretized into bins of size $\Delta$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] which is, as said before, referred to as the differential entropy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This means that the differential entropy *is not* a limit of the Shannon entropy for *n* → ∞.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Rather, it differs from the limit of the Shannon entropy by an infinite offset (see also the article on information dimension).
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It turns out as a result that, unlike the Shannon entropy, the differential entropy is *not* in general a good measure of uncertainty or information.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, the differential entropy can be negative; also it is not invariant under continuous co-ordinate transformations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This problem may be illustrated by a change of units when *x* is a dimensioned variable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] *f*(*x*) will then have the units of 1/*x*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The argument of the logarithm must be dimensionless, otherwise it is improper, so that the differential entropy as given above will be improper.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If *Δ* is some "standard" value of *x* (i.e.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] "bin size") and therefore has the same units, then a modified differential entropy may be written in proper form as: $\mathrm {H} =\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }f(x)\log(f(x)\,\Delta )\,dx,$ and the result will be the same for any choice of units for *x*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In fact, the limit of discrete entropy as $N\rightarrow \infty$ would also include a term of $\log(N)$ , which would in general be infinite.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] This is expected: continuous variables would typically have infinite entropy when discretized.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The limiting density of discrete points is really a measure of how much easier a distribution is to describe than a distribution that is uniform over its quantization scheme.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Another useful measure of entropy that works equally well in the discrete and the continuous case is the **relative entropy** of a distribution.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It is defined as the Kullback–Leibler divergence from the distribution to a reference measure *m* as follows.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In this form the relative entropy generalizes (up to change in sign) both the discrete entropy, where the measure *m* is the counting measure, and the differential entropy, where the measure *m* is the Lebesgue measure.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] If the measure *m* is itself a probability distribution, the relative entropy is non-negative, and zero if *p* = *m* as measures.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] It is defined for any measure space, hence coordinate independent and invariant under co-ordinate reparameterizations if one properly takes into account the transformation of the measure *m*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The relative entropy, and (implicitly) entropy and differential entropy, do depend on the "reference" measure *m*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Terence Tao used entropy to make a useful connection trying to solve the Erdős discrepancy problem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] And in an interval [n, n+H] the sum over that interval could become arbitrarily large.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] For example, a sequence of +1's (which are values of *X**H* could take) have trivially low entropy and their sum would become big.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] But the key insight was showing a reduction in entropy by non negligible amounts as one expands H leading inturn to unbounded growth of a mathematical object over this random variable is equivalent to showing the unbounded growth per the Erdős discrepancy problem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The proof is quite involved and it brought together breakthroughs not just in novel use of Shannon entropy, but also it used the Liouville function along with averages of modulated multiplicative functions in short intervals.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Proving it also broke the "parity barrier" for this specific problem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] While the use of Shannon entropy in the proof is novel it is likely to open new research in this direction.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Entropy has become a useful quantity in combinatorics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] We sketch how Loomis–Whitney follows from this: Indeed, let *X* be a uniformly distributed random variable with values in *A* and so that each point in *A* occurs with equal probability.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Then (by the further properties of entropy mentioned above) Η(*X*) = log|*A*|, where |*A*| denotes the cardinality of *A*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Now use this to bound the right side of Shearer's inequality and exponentiate the opposite sides of the resulting inequality you obtain.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] A nice interpretation of this is that the number of binary strings of length *n* with exactly *k* many 1's is approximately $2^{n\mathrm {H} (k/n)}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Machine learning techniques arise largely from statistics and also information theory.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In general, entropy is a measure of uncertainty and the objective of machine learning is to minimize uncertainty.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Decision tree learning algorithms use relative entropy to determine the decision rules that govern the data at each node.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The information gain in decision trees $IG(Y,X)$ , which is equal to the difference between the entropy of Y and the conditional entropy of Y given X , quantifies the expected information, or the reduction in entropy, from additionally knowing the value of an attribute X .
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The information gain is used to identify which attributes of the dataset provide the most information and should be used to split the nodes of the tree optimally.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Bayesian inference models often apply the principle of maximum entropy to obtain prior probability distributions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] The idea is that the distribution that best represents the current state of knowledge of a system is the one with the largest entropy, and is therefore suitable to be the prior.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] Classification in machine learning performed by logistic regression or artificial neural networks often employs a standard loss function, called cross-entropy loss, that minimizes the average cross entropy between ground truth and predicted distributions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/entropy-information-theory] In general, cross entropy is a measure of the differences between two datasets similar to the KL divergence (also known as relative entropy).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A **Markov decision process** (**MDP**) is a mathematical model for sequential decision making when outcomes are uncertain.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It is a type of stochastic decision process, and is often solved using the methods of stochastic dynamic programming.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Originating from operations research in the 1950s, MDPs have since gained recognition in a variety of fields, including ecology, economics, healthcare, telecommunications and reinforcement learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning utilizes the MDP framework to model the interaction between a learning agent and its environment.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In this framework, the interaction is characterized by states, actions, and rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The MDP framework is designed to provide a simplified representation of key elements of artificial intelligence challenges.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This modeling framework incorporates the understanding of cause and effect, the management of uncertainty and nondeterminism, and the pursuit of explicit goals.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The name comes from its connection to Markov chains, a concept developed by the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The "Markov" in "Markov decision process" refers to the underlying structure of state transitions that still follow the Markov property.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The process is called a "decision process" because it involves making decisions that influence these state transitions, extending the concept of a Markov chain into the realm of decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A policy function $\pi$ is a (potentially probabilistic) mapping from state space ( S ) to action space ( A ).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The goal in a Markov decision process is to find a good "policy" for the decision maker: a function $\pi$ that specifies the action $\pi (s)$ that the decision maker will choose when in state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Once a Markov decision process is combined with a policy in this way, this fixes the action for each state and the resulting combination behaves like a Markov chain (since the action chosen in state s is completely determined by $\pi (s)$ ).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] where $\ \gamma \$ is the discount factor satisfying $0\leq \ \gamma \ \leq \ 1$ , which is usually close to 1 (for example, $\gamma =1/(1+r)$ for some discount rate r ).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A lower discount factor makes the decision maker more short-sighted, in that it comparatively disregards the effect that following its current policy has at times lying further in the future.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Another possible, but strictly related, objective that is commonly used is the $H-$ step return.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This time, instead of using a discount factor $\ \gamma \$ , the agent is interested only in the first H steps of the process, with each reward having the same weight.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Compared to the previous objective, the latter one is more used in Learning Theory.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A policy that maximizes the function above is called an **optimal policy** and is usually denoted $\pi ^{*}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A particular MDP may have multiple distinct optimal policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Because of the Markov property, it can be shown that the optimal policy is a function of the current state, as assumed above.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] When $R_{a}(s,s')$ is deterministic, there will always exist an optimal policy $\pi ^{*}$ which is deterministic as well.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Assume that R is deterministic, meaning for constants $a,s,s'$ the value $R_{a}(s,s')$ is also constant.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] From inspection, notice that this fixed point is the value function associated to the following policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] By unrolling the Bellman recursion, one can show that $V^{*}$ is indeed optimal (simultaneously for all states) over the set of deterministic policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Consider the case where $\pi$ is probabilistic, meaning the action taken $a:=\pi (s)$ is a random variable.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] One can show any such non-deterministic policy is dominated by deterministic $\pi ^{*}$ as follows.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In many cases, it is difficult to represent the transition probability distributions, $P_{a}(s,s')$ , explicitly.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In such cases, a simulator can be used to model the MDP implicitly by providing samples from the transition distributions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] One common form of implicit MDP model is an episodic environment simulator that can be started from an initial state and yields a subsequent state and reward every time it receives an action input.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In this manner, trajectories of states, actions, and rewards, often called **episodes** may be produced.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Another form of simulator is a **generative model**, a single step simulator that can generate samples of the next state and reward given any state and action.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] (Note that this is a different meaning from the term generative model in the context of statistical classification.) In algorithms that are expressed using pseudocode, G is often used to represent a generative model.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] For example, the expression $s',r\gets G(s,a)$ might denote the action of sampling from the generative model where s and a are the current state and action, and $s'$ and r are the new state and reward.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Compared to an episodic simulator, a generative model has the advantage that it can yield data from any state, not only those encountered in a trajectory.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] These model classes form a hierarchy of information content: an explicit model trivially yields a generative model through sampling from the distributions, and repeated application of a generative model yields an episodic simulator.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In the opposite direction, it is only possible to learn approximate models through regression.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The type of model available for a particular MDP plays a significant role in determining which solution algorithms are appropriate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] An example of MDP is the Pole-Balancing model, which comes from classic control theory.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Solutions for MDPs with finite state and action spaces may be found through a variety of methods such as dynamic programming.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The algorithms in this section apply to MDPs with finite state and action spaces and explicitly given transition probabilities and reward functions, but the basic concepts may be extended to handle other problem classes, for example using function approximation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Also, some processes with countably infinite state and action spaces can be *exactly* reduced to ones with finite state and action spaces.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The standard family of algorithms to calculate optimal policies for finite state and action MDPs requires storage for two arrays indexed by state: *value* V , which contains real values, and *policy* $\pi$ , which contains actions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] At the end of the algorithm, $\pi$ will contain the solution and $V(s)$ will contain the discounted sum of the rewards to be earned (on average) by following that solution from state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The algorithm has two steps, (1) a value update and (2) a policy update, which are repeated in some order for all the states until no further changes take place.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Both recursively update a new estimation of the optimal policy and state value using an older estimation of those values.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Their order depends on the variant of the algorithm; one can also do them for all states at once or state by state, and more often to some states than others.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] As long as no state is permanently excluded from either of the steps, the algorithm will eventually arrive at the correct solution.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In value iteration (Bellman 1957), which is also called backward induction, the $\pi$ function is not used; instead, the value of $\pi (s)$ is calculated within $V(s)$ whenever it is needed.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Value iteration starts at $i=0$ and $V_{0}$ as a guess of the value function.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It then iterates, repeatedly computing $V_{i+1}$ for all states s , until V converges with the left-hand side equal to the right-hand side (which is the "Bellman equation" for this problem).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Lloyd Shapley's 1953 paper on stochastic games included as a special case the value iteration method for MDPs, but this was recognized only later on.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Value iteration is guaranteed to converge for $\gamma <1$ by the Banach fixed-point theorem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that a given contraction mapping has a unique fixed point; further, one can asymptotically approach this fixed points by iterated application of the contraction mapping.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It then suffices to show that value iteration is a contraction mapping, which is shown below for $\gamma <1$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In policy iteration, one first performs *Value Determination* by solving for V from the linear system described in step one, then performs *Policy Improvement* by computing $\pi$ as in step two, then repeats both steps until the policy converges.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Since policy iteration effectively interleaves a linear inverse problem with a nonlinear operation, it may interpreted as a type of relaxation method.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This variant has the advantage that there is a definite stopping condition.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Since there is a unique solution V for each policy $\pi$ , the algorithm is completed once the *Policy Improvement* produces the same policy twice consecutively.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] While there are situations where policy iteration may be faster than value iteration (e.g. when the action space is significantly larger than the state space), policy iteration is usually slower than value iteration for a large number of possible states.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In modified policy iteration (van Nunen 1976; Puterman & Shin 1978), step one is repeated several times, and then step two is performed once.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Then step one is again repeated several times and so on.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Algorithms for finding optimal policies with time complexity polynomial in the size of the problem representation exist for finite MDPs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Thus, decision problems based on MDPs are in computational complexity class P.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] However, due to the curse of dimensionality, the size of the problem representation is often exponential in the number of state and action variables, limiting exact solution techniques to problems that have a compact representation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] A Markov decision process is a stochastic game with only one player.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The solution above assumes that the state s is known when action is to be taken; otherwise $\pi (s)$ cannot be calculated.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] When this assumption is not true, the problem is called a partially observable Markov decision process or POMDP.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Constrained Markov decision processes (CMDPS) are extensions to Markov decision process (MDPs).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] There are three fundamental differences between MDPs and CMDPs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The method of Lagrange multipliers applies to CMDPs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Many Lagrangian-based algorithms have been developed.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] There are a number of applications for CMDPs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It has recently been used in motion planning scenarios in robotics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In discrete-time Markov Decision Processes, decisions are made at discrete time intervals.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] However, for **continuous-time Markov decision processes**, decisions can be made at any time the decision maker chooses.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In comparison to discrete-time Markov decision processes, continuous-time Markov decision processes can better model the decision-making process for a system that has continuous dynamics, i.e., the system dynamics are defined by ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This modelling framework can be applied to areas such as queueing systems, epidemic processes, and population processes.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Like the discrete-time Markov decision processes, in continuous-time Markov decision processes the agent aims to find the optimal *policy* that would maximize the expected cumulative reward.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] If the state space and action space are finite, we could use linear programming to find the optimal policy, which was one of the earliest approaches applied.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Here we only consider the ergodic model, which means our continuous-time MDP becomes an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain under a stationary policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Under this assumption, although the decision maker can make a decision at any time in the current state, there is no benefit in taking multiple actions.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] It is better to take an action only at the time when system is transitioning from the current state to another state.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] If there exists a function h , then ${\bar {V}}^{*}$ will be the smallest g satisfying the above equation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] $y(i,a)$ is a feasible solution to the D-LP if $y(i,a)$ is nonnative and satisfied the constraints in the D-LP problem.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] for all feasible solution $y(i,a)$ to the D-LP.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Once we have found the optimal solution $y^{*}(i,a)$ , we can use it to establish the optimal policies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In continuous-time MDP, if the state space and action space are continuous, the optimal criterion could be found by solving the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman (HJB) partial differential equation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] $D(\cdot )$ is the terminal reward function, $s(t)$ is the system state vector, $a(t)$ is the system control vector we try to find. $f(\cdot )$ shows how the state vector changes over time.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning is an interdisciplinary area of machine learning and optimal control that has, as main objective, finding an approximately optimal policy for MDPs where transition probabilities and rewards are unknown.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning can solve Markov-Decision processes without explicit specification of the transition probabilities which are instead needed to perform policy iteration.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In this setting, transition probabilities and rewards must be learned from experience, i.e. by letting an agent interact with the MDP for a given number of steps.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] While this function is also unknown, experience during learning is based on $(s,a)$ pairs (together with the outcome $s'$ ; that is, "I was in state s and I tried doing a and $s'$ happened").
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Thus, one has an array Q and uses experience to update it directly.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Another application of MDP process in machine learning theory is called learning automata.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] This is also one type of reinforcement learning if the environment is stochastic.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The first detail **learning automata** paper is surveyed by Narendra and Thathachar (1974), which were originally described explicitly as finite-state automata.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Similar to reinforcement learning, a learning automata algorithm also has the advantage of solving the problem when probability or rewards are unknown.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The difference between learning automata and Q-learning is that the former technique omits the memory of Q-values, but updates the action probability directly to find the learning result.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Learning automata is a learning scheme with a rigorous proof of convergence.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The states of such an automaton correspond to the states of a "discrete-state discrete-parameter Markov process".
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] At each time step *t* = 0,1,2,3,..., the automaton reads an input from its environment, updates P(*t*) to P(*t* + 1) by *A*, randomly chooses a successor state according to the probabilities P(*t* + 1) and outputs the corresponding action.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The automaton's environment, in turn, reads the action and sends the next input to the automaton.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Other than the rewards, a Markov decision process $(S,A,P)$ can be understood in terms of Category theory.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Namely, let ${\mathcal {A}}$ denote the free monoid with generating set *A*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Let **Dist** denote the Kleisli category of the Giry monad.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] Then a functor ${\mathcal {A}}\to \mathbf {Dist}$ encodes both the set *S* of states and the probability function *P*.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In this way, Markov decision processes could be generalized from monoids (categories with one object) to arbitrary categories.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] One can call the result $({\mathcal {C}},F:{\mathcal {C}}\to \mathbf {Dist} )$ a *context-dependent Markov decision process*, because moving from one object to another in ${\mathcal {C}}$ changes the set of available actions and the set of possible states.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] The terminology and notation for MDPs are not entirely settled.
[src:soft-actor-critic/markov-decision-process] In addition, the notation for the transition probability varies.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] In reinforcement learning (RL), a **model-free** algorithm is an algorithm which does not estimate the *transition probability distribution* (and the *reward function*) associated with the Markov decision process (MDP), which, in RL, represents the problem to be solved.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] The transition probability distribution (or transition model) and the reward function are often collectively called the "model" of the environment (or MDP), hence the name "model-free".
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] A model-free RL algorithm can be thought of as an "explicit" trial-and-error algorithm.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Typical examples of model-free algorithms include Monte Carlo (MC) RL, SARSA, and Q-learning.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Monte Carlo estimation is a central component of many model-free RL algorithms.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] The MC learning algorithm is essentially an important branch of generalized policy iteration, which has two periodically alternating steps: policy evaluation (PEV) and policy improvement (PIM).
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] In this framework, each policy is first evaluated by its corresponding value function.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Then, based on the evaluation result, greedy search is completed to produce a better policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] The MC estimation is mainly applied to the first step of policy evaluation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] The simplest idea is used to judge the effectiveness of the current policy, which is to average the returns of all collected samples.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] As more experience is accumulated, the estimate will converge to the true value by the law of large numbers.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Hence, MC policy evaluation does not require any prior knowledge of the environment dynamics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Instead, only experience is needed (i.e., samples of state, action, and reward), which is generated from interacting with an environment (which may be real or simulated).
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Value function estimation is crucial for model-free RL algorithms.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Unlike MC methods, temporal difference (TD) methods learn this function by reusing existing value estimates.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] TD learning has the ability to learn from an incomplete sequence of events without waiting for the final outcome.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] It can also approximate the future return as a function of the current state.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Similar to MC, TD only uses experience to estimate the value function without knowing any prior knowledge of the environment dynamics.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] The advantage of TD lies in the fact that it can update the value function based on its current estimate.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Therefore, TD learning algorithms can learn from incomplete episodes or continuing tasks in a step-by-step manner, while MC must be implemented in an episode-by-episode fashion.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Model-free RL algorithms can start from a blank policy candidate and achieve superhuman performance in many complex tasks, including Atari games, StarCraft and Go.
[src:soft-actor-critic/model-free-reinforcement-learning] Deep neural networks are responsible for recent artificial intelligence breakthroughs, and they can be combined with RL to create superhuman agents such as Google DeepMind's AlphaGo.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In policy-based RL, the actor is a parameterized policy function $\pi _{\theta }$ , where $\theta$ are the parameters of the actor.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The actor takes as argument the state of the environment s and produces a probability distribution $\pi _{\theta }(\cdot \mid s)$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is discrete, then $\sum _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)=1$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] If the action space is continuous, then $\int _{a}\pi _{\theta }(a\mid s)\mathrm {d} a=1$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The **policy gradient** is defined as $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Different policy gradient methods stochastically estimate the policy gradient in different ways.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The goal of any policy gradient method is to iteratively maximize $J(\theta )$ by gradient ascent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Since the key part of any policy gradient method is the stochastic estimation of the policy gradient, they are also studied under the title of "Monte Carlo gradient estimation".
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The **REINFORCE algorithm**, introduced by Ronald J.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Williams in 1992, was the first policy gradient method.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] By the tower law and the previous lemma.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The score function $\nabla _{\theta }\ln \pi _{\theta }(A_{t}\mid S_{t})$ can be interpreted as the direction in the parameter space that increases the probability of taking action $A_{t}$ in state $S_{t}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Here, $\alpha _{i}$ is the learning rate at update step i .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] REINFORCE is an **on-policy** algorithm, meaning that the trajectories used for the update must be sampled from the current policy $\pi _{\theta }$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This can lead to high variance in the updates, as the returns $R(\tau )$ can vary significantly between trajectories.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Many variants of REINFORCE have been introduced, under the title of **variance reduction**.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This can be proven by applying the previous lemma.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] If ${\textstyle b_{i}}$ is chosen well, such that ${\textstyle b_{i}(S_{t})\approx \sum _{\tau =t}^{T}(\gamma ^{\tau }R_{\tau })=\gamma ^{t}V^{\pi _{\theta _{i}}}(S_{t})}$ , this could significantly decrease variance in the gradient estimation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] One common approach is to train a separate function that estimates the value function, and use that as the baseline.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This is one of the actor-critic methods, where the policy function is the actor and the value function is the critic.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Some more possible ${\textstyle \Psi _{t}}$ are as follows, with very similar proofs.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The natural policy gradient method is a variant of the policy gradient method, proposed by Sham Kakade in 2001.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Unlike standard policy gradient methods, which depend on the choice of parameters $\theta$ (making updates coordinate-dependent), the natural policy gradient aims to provide a coordinate-free update, which is geometrically "natural".
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Inverting $F(\theta )$ is computationally intensive, especially for high-dimensional parameters (e.g., neural networks).
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Practical implementations often use approximations.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The natural gradient descent is theoretically optimal, *if* the objective is truly a quadratic function, but this is only an approximation.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] TRPO's line search and KL constraint attempts to restrict the solution to within a "trust region" in which this approximation does not break down.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This makes TRPO more robust in practice.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Note that in general, other surrogate advantages are possible: $L(\theta ,\theta _{i})=\mathbb {E} _{s,a\sim \pi _{\theta _{i}}}\left[{\frac {\pi _{\theta }(a|s)}{\pi _{\theta _{i}}(a|s)}}\Psi ^{\pi _{\theta _{i}}}(s,a)\right]$ where $\Psi$ is any linear sum of the previously mentioned type.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Indeed, OpenAI recommended using the Generalized Advantage Estimate, instead of the plain advantage $A^{\pi _{\theta }}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The surrogate advantage $L(\theta ,\theta _{t})$ is designed to align with the policy gradient $\nabla _{\theta }J(\theta )$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Thus it is a "surrogate" of the real objective.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This reduces the problem to a quadratic optimization, yielding the natural policy gradient update: $\theta _{i+1}=\theta _{i}+{\sqrt {\frac {2\epsilon }{g^{T}F^{-1}g}}}F^{-1}g.$ So far, this is essentially the same as natural gradient method.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] A further improvement is proximal policy optimization (PPO), which avoids even computing $F(\theta )$ and $F(\theta )^{-1}$ via a first-order approximation using clipped probability ratios.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In words, gradient-ascending the new surrogate advantage function means that, at some state $s,a$ , if the advantage is positive: $A^{\pi _{\theta _{t}}}(s,a)>0$ , then the gradient should direct $\theta$ towards the direction that increases the probability of performing action a under the state s .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] However, as soon as $\theta$ has changed so much that $\pi _{\theta }(a|s)\geq (1+\epsilon )\pi _{\theta _{t}}(a|s)$ , then the gradient should stop pointing it in that direction.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Thus, PPO avoids pushing the parameter update too hard, and avoids changing the policy too much.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] To be more precise, to update $\theta _{t}$ to $\theta _{t+1}$ requires multiple update steps on the same batch of data.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] It would initialize $\theta =\theta _{t}$ , then repeatedly apply gradient descent (such as the Adam optimizer) to update $\theta$ until the surrogate advantage has stabilized.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] It would then assign $\theta _{t+1}$ to $\theta$ , and do it again.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] During this inner-loop, the first update to $\theta$ would not hit the $1-\epsilon ,1+\epsilon$ bounds, but as $\theta$ is updated further and further away from $\theta _{t}$ , it eventually starts hitting the bounds.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] For each such bound hit, the corresponding gradient becomes zero, and thus PPO avoid updating $\theta$ too far away from $\theta _{t}$ .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This is important, because the surrogate loss assumes that the state-action pair $s,a$ is sampled from what the agent would see if the agent runs the policy $\pi _{\theta _{t}}$ , but policy gradient should be on-policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] So, as $\theta$ changes, the surrogate loss becomes more and more *off*-policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This is why keeping $\theta$ *proximal* to $\theta _{t}$ is necessary.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This has been used in training reasoning language models with reinforcement learning from human feedback.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] The Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) is a minor variant of PPO that omits the value function estimator V .
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] That is, it is the standard score of the rewards.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] As before, the KL penalty term can be applied to encourage the trained policy to stay close to a reference policy.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] GRPO was first proposed in the context of training reasoning language models by researchers at DeepSeek.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] Methods like TRPO, PPO and natural policy gradient share a common idea - while the policy should be updated in the direction of the policy gradient, the update should be done in a safe and stable manner, typically measured by some distance with respect to the policy before the update.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] A similar notion of update stability is found in proximal convex optimization techniques like Mirror Descent.
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] This leads to reconsidering the policy update procedure as an optimization procedure aimed at finding an optimal policy, in the (non-convex) optimization landscape of the underlying Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:soft-actor-critic/policy-gradient-method] In fact, the KL divergence penalty also appears in the original PPO paper, suggesting the MDPO perspective as a theoretical unification of the main derivation concepts behind many concurrent policy gradient techniques.
